|[[Ten-sided die|10]]||[[pentagonal trapezohedron]]||[[Image:Trapezohedron5.jpg|30px|Pentagonal trapezohedron]]||Each face is a kite. The die has two sharp corners, where five kites meet, and ten blunter corners, where three kites meet. The ten faces usually bear numbers from zero to nine, rather than one to ten (zero being read as "ten" in many applications). Often all [[odd number]]ed faces converge at one sharp corner, and the [[even number|even]] ones at the other. The sum of the numbers on opposite faces is usually 9 (numbered 0–9) or 11 (number 1–10).
